<div class="bg-zinc-950 text-zinc-100">
  <.marketing_nav current_user={@current_user} current={:docs} />

  <section class="py-16 sm:py-24">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 lg:px-8">
      <.breadcrumbs items={[{"Docs", ~p"/docs"}, {"Signed dispatch", nil}]} />
      <.marketing_heading tag="h1" scale={:hero} class="mt-2">
        Signed dispatch
      </.marketing_heading>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-8 text-zinc-400 text-pretty">
        By default a runner trusts the control plane to tell it what to run. Signed dispatch
        removes that trust: with enforcement on, a runner executes an action only when it carries a
        valid Ed25519 signature a real person produced in their own MCP client. The control plane
        relays that signature — it holds no private key, so it can't forge, alter, redirect, or
        replay one, and it can't originate a run at all. The signature, not the cloud, is the
        authority.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-500">
        It's opt-in per runner and a deliberate trade: while it's on, the portal Run button,
        runbooks, scheduled runs, and API keys can't dispatch to that host — only a signed MCP call
        runs. Turn it on where "a real human asked for this" must be cryptographically true, not
        just policy-checked.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 text-balance">How it works</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        Three parties, one of them untrusted. Here is the path a signed dispatch takes:
      </p>
      <ol class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-zinc-300 list-decimal pl-6">
        <li>
          <strong>The MCP client signs.</strong>
          When you call an action, the client builds a canonical message — the action id, a hash of
          the arguments, a one-time nonce, and a timestamp — and signs it with an Ed25519 private
          key that never leaves your machine.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>The control plane relays.</strong>
          The portal stores and forwards the signature verbatim inside the dispatch. It can't change
          the action or its arguments without invalidating the signature, and it has no key to mint
          a new one.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>The runner verifies, then runs.</strong>
          It checks the signature against a public key in its own config, checks the timestamp is
          inside its freshness window, and checks the nonce hasn't been seen before. Only then does
          it execute. Anything else comes back as a failed run with a reason.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <div class="mt-6 rounded-xl border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-950/60 p-5 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <strong class="text-zinc-100">The trust anchor is the key itself.</strong>
        A runner trusts only the key ids listed in its own config, established out of band — so a
        dispatch signed for one trust domain can't be run by a host that doesn't hold its key. The
        signature binds the action, args, nonce, and time, not a runner name the signer and the
        cloud would have to agree on. Use a distinct key per environment — or per runner — so a
        dispatch signed for staging can't be relayed to prod.
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 text-balance">Turn it on</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        Generate a keypair, install the public half on the runner, hand the private half to your MCP
        client, and reload. The keypair is generated offline — the private key is printed locally
        and sent nowhere.
      </p>

      <p class="mt-6 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <strong class="text-zinc-200">1. Generate a keypair on the runner host.</strong>
        It prints a ready-to-paste config block (the public key) and two env vars (the private key).
      </p>
      <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
        <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300"><span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> emisar keygen --key-id mcp-prod-2026</pre>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <strong class="text-zinc-200">2. Install the public key</strong>
        in <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">/etc/emisar/config.yaml</code>. The
        public key is safe to commit.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
        <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300"><span class="text-zinc-500"># /etc/emisar/config.yaml</span>
signing:
  enforce_signatures: true
  max_attestation_age: 24h
  trusted_keys:
    - key_id: mcp-prod-2026
      public_key: &lt;hex from keygen&gt;</pre>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <strong class="text-zinc-200">3. Give the private key to your MCP client</strong>
        as environment variables — never on the portal, never in version control
        (see <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/connect-an-llm"}
          class="text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >
          connect an LLM
        </.link>).
      </p>
      <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
        <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300"><span class="text-zinc-500"># on the machine running your MCP client — not the portal, not git</span>
EMISAR_SIGNING_KEY=&lt;hex seed from keygen&gt;
EMISAR_SIGNING_KEY_ID=mcp-prod-2026</pre>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <strong class="text-zinc-200">4. Apply it.</strong>
        Reload the runner — it rebuilds the verifier from config and re-advertises, so enforcement
        (and every later rotation) takes effect live, no restart and no dropped runs.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
        <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300"><span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> sudo systemctl reload emisar</pre>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        Then check it landed: the Runner page shows <strong class="text-zinc-200">Signed dispatch
          only</strong>
        and the Run button is disabled, an MCP
        <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">tools/call</code>
        runs, and an operator or runbook dispatch is refused with a clear message.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 text-balance">
        Distributing keys across a fleet
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        The hard part of any signing scheme isn't the math — it's getting the right public key onto
        every host and keeping it current. emisar keeps that boring on purpose.
      </p>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <strong class="text-zinc-200">The public key is config, not a secret.</strong>
            Ship it the way you already ship the rest of
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">config.yaml</code>
            — cloud-init, Packer, Ansible, a golden image, your
            infra repo. It's the same shape as an SSH certificate authority's public key or an
            OpenBSD signify key: one public file, pinned on the host, distributed through a channel
            you already trust.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <strong class="text-zinc-200">
              The control plane is deliberately not the distributor.
            </strong>
            emisar never holds or hands out your signing keys — that's the whole point. Don't route
            them through the portal; route them through whatever already provisions the host. The
            one step you can't avoid is getting that first public key onto the box through a trusted
            channel, which is the same channel that writes its config.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <strong class="text-zinc-200">
              Pick the granularity that matches how you operate.
            </strong>
            One key per environment — staging, prod — is the usual right answer: a prod-signed
            action can't run on staging or the reverse, and the operator's client is set for the
            environment they're in. A distinct key per runner is maximum isolation (a dispatch
            signed for one host can never be relayed to another) at the cost of the signer selecting
            the matching key per target. A single fleet-wide key is simplest to run but gives up
            that redirect protection.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <strong class="text-zinc-200">The private key is the crown jewel.</strong>
            The Ed25519 seed in
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">EMISAR_SIGNING_KEY</code>
            is what mints authority. Generate it offline, keep it in your secrets store or password
            manager, and never let it reach the portal or git. Whoever holds it can sign actions for
            every runner that trusts its key id.
          </span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 text-balance">Rotating keys</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">trusted_keys</code>
        is a list, so rotation is add-then-remove with zero downtime — a reload applies each step
        live, rebuilding the verifier from config without dropping the connection or any in-flight
        run.
      </p>
      <ol class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-zinc-300 list-decimal pl-6">
        <li>
          Add the new key alongside the old in every runner's config and reload. Both keys verify
          now.
        </li>
        <li>
          Switch your MCP client to the new <code>EMISAR_SIGNING_KEY</code>
          and <code>EMISAR_SIGNING_KEY_ID</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
          Remove the old key from the config and reload again — once no live dispatch could still
          carry its signature.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        That last condition has a precise answer: a signature is only valid inside the
        ±<code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">max_attestation_age</code> window, so waiting one window after you stop signing with the old key guarantees no valid
        old-key dispatch remains. Step three can't strand a run.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 text-balance">Revoking a key</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        To revoke a compromised key, remove it from
        <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">trusted_keys</code>
        and reload every runner that trusts it — it stops verifying immediately, no restart. Be
        clear-eyed about two things:
      </p>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <strong class="text-zinc-200">Revocation is a fleet operation, not a switch.</strong>
            A key is dead only on the runners that have received the updated config. Push the removal
            through the same pipeline you used to distribute it, and treat "every runner reloaded"
            as the completion bar — the control plane can't do this for you, by design.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <strong class="text-zinc-200">
              The freshness window bounds replay, not a key holder.
            </strong>
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">max_attestation_age</code>
            limits how long one captured signature can be replayed; it does not limit someone who
            holds the private key — they can mint fresh, valid signatures until you remove the public
            key. A trusted key has no automatic expiry, so a leaked seed means: rotate now, across
            the fleet.
          </span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 text-balance">Best practices</h2>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <strong class="text-zinc-200">One key per environment, named for its life.</strong>
            A key id like
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">mcp-prod-2026</code>
            says what it's for and when to roll it. Rotate on a cadence, not only after an incident.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <strong class="text-zinc-200">Keep the public key in your infra repo.</strong>
            Let config management own it next to the host's <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">config.yaml</code>; never
            hand-copy it to one box at a time. A diff and a deploy is your rotation record.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <strong class="text-zinc-200">Set the window against your real SLAs.</strong>
            If you combine signing with approvals, a parked run is re-dispatched with its
            <em>original</em>
            signature — so
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">max_attestation_age</code>
            must comfortably exceed your approval turnaround, or a slow approval is refused as stale.
            A wider window means a longer replay exposure: choose deliberately
            (see <.link
              navigate={~p"/docs/policies-and-approvals"}
              class="text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
            >
              policies &amp; approvals
            </.link>).
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <strong class="text-zinc-200">Don't share one key across trust domains.</strong>
            A fleet-wide key trades away redirect protection. Reach for it only when per-environment
            keys are genuinely too much to operate — and write down that you did.
          </span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 text-balance">
        What it does and doesn't guarantee
      </h2>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <strong class="text-zinc-200">Integrity, not availability.</strong>
            A compromised control plane can still withhold or refuse to relay your signed dispatch.
            Signing stops it from forging one; it can't force it to deliver yours.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <strong class="text-zinc-200">Replay across a restart or reload.</strong>
            The nonce cache is in memory. A restart — or a reload that rebuilds the verifier —
            forgets which nonces it has seen, so a replay within
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">max_attestation_age</code>
            after one could pass. Persisting the cache is future hardening.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <strong class="text-zinc-200">Queued while offline.</strong>
            A dispatch that sits queued longer than
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">max_attestation_age</code>
            (runner offline, or a slow approval) is refused as stale and must be re-issued.
          </span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 text-balance">
        Troubleshooting a refusal
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        A refused dispatch comes back as a failed run whose error names the cause:
      </p>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">signature_required</code>
            — the dispatch carried no signature (it came from the portal, a runbook, or an API key,
            or the MCP client isn't configured to sign). Run it from a client with
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">EMISAR_SIGNING_KEY</code>
            set.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">unknown_key</code>
            — the signature's key id isn't in this runner's <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">trusted_keys</code>. Add the public
            key and reload, or point the client at a key the runner trusts.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">stale</code>
            — the timestamp is outside the freshness window (clock skew, a long-queued run, or a
            slow approval). Re-issue the run, check host clocks (NTP), or widen
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">max_attestation_age</code>
            if approvals are the cause.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">bad_signature</code>
            — the signature doesn't verify against the action, args, nonce, and time as relayed.
            Wrong key, or the client and runner disagree on it — re-mint and re-distribute.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-600">—</span>
          <span>
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">replayed</code>
            — this nonce was already used. The client double-sent; re-issue with a fresh dispatch.
          </span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="mt-12 flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-3 border-t border-zinc-900 pt-8 text-sm">
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/security-model"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >
          Where it sits in the threat model <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/runners"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >
          Fleet config &amp; reload <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/connect-an-llm"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >
          Set the signing key on your client <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <.marketing_footer />
</div>
